@node description "Description"    

    Dofile recognizes the filetype using datatypes.library and launches the
    corresponding tool.

    This enables you to use your favorite viewer/player/editor instead of
    Multiview and still keep the advantage of the datatypes.library
    filetype recognition. But Dofile can also recognize files using filename
    matching.
    Both datatypes (and filename patterns) can be any AmigaDOS pattern. This
    makes it easy to group datatypes together that uses the same viewer. 

    Very useful when installed as a do-it-all appicon in Toolmanager. It's
    also possible to use Dofile as default tool in Workbench project icons.
    You can even use a ToolAlias utility to redirect all calls to Dofile.
    And of course it also works nicely from CLI.

    Now you only have one global config file to change when you install eg.
    a new JPEG viewer.

    Other features:
    * Changes directory to the datafile directory if possible. Making it
      easier to load other files in eg. a text viewer.
    * Handles icons that has no matching file perfectly
    * Has a SHOWDATATYPE switch that displays the datatype of a file in a
      requester. And much more info when coupled with the VERBOSE switch.
    * Uses filenotification to reread the prefs file each time you change it.
    * It's possible to set the stacksize of the command.
    * Dofile opens a filerequester if you don't pass it a file as argument. If
      you pass it a directory it will open the requester in that directory.

@endnode
@node requirements "Requirements"

    Workbench 3.x with lots of datatypes installed. 

    rmh.library. v6.5 included with this archive.

    RexxMast.

    c:requestfile

    If you want to use Dofile as default tool in project icons you either need
    WB 3.5 or the included RxWB tool.

@endnode
@node installation "Installation"

    Copy "Dofile.rexx" to rexx: 
    @{" Do it " system "copy Dofile.rexx rexx:"}

    Copy the example "dofile.prefs" to s: 
    @{" Do it " system "copy dofile.prefs s:"}

    If you don't have WB 3.5 copy "RxWB" to rexx: and rename it to Dofile.
    @{" Do it " system "copy RxWB rexx:Dofile"}

    Copy "rmh.library" to libs: if you do not have it already.
    @{" Do it " system "copy libs/rmh.library libs:"}

    Copy the "Dostart.info" icon to your WBStartup drawer if you want
    Dofile installed each time you boot.
    @{" Do it " system "copy Dostart.info sys:wbstartup"}

@endnode
@node configuration "Configuration"
                        
    Please read the @{" Dofile and Multiview " link multiview} section and have a look at 
    the @{" example config file " link dofile.prefs/main}

    Edit the Dofile.prefs file. Each line consists of a datatype name and
    the associated command. Blank lines or lines that start with a
    semicolon are ignored. The rest are parsed using ReadArgs() with this
    template: 

    @{b}DATATYPE/A,COMMAND/A,STACK/K/N,PATTERN/S,PREFIX/K@{ub}

    @{b}DATATYPE@{ub}
    DATATYPE is what datatypes.library knows the file as. If in doubt about
    the datatype simply run Dofile with the @{" SHOWDATATYPE " link usage} switch and check the
    requester (Eg: rx dofile SHOWDATATYPE ram:disk.info).
    You can use AmigaDos patterns to group more than one datatype with the
    same command. 

    @{b}COMMAND@{ub}
    COMMAND is the corresponding viewer/player/editor/etc.
    Some DATATYPE and COMMAND examples:
    GIF                           cc:visage
    "Amiga .info File"            cc:fasticon
    (REXX|C++-Source|C-Source)    c:ed
    "(Bitmap Font|Outline Font)"  "sys:utilities/multiview REQUESTER"

    @{b}PATTERN@{ub}
    The PATTERN switch tells Dofile to do filename matching instead instead of
    checking the datatype of the file. Only use this switch if absolutely
    necessary - there is a datatype descriptor for almost any type of file.
    Have a look in the @{" desc " link dtdesc} drawer.
    A few PATTERN examples:
    #?.c                          c:edit PATTERN
    #?.(avi|qt|mov)               "rx rexx:startamp.rexx" STACK=300000 PATTERN
    The PATTERN keyword only works on ascii, binary or iff files (Ie: Not on
    files that you have a datatype descriptor for).
    
    @{b}STACK@{ub}
    The STACK keyword is used to set the stack of the COMMAND. The default is
    8192 bytes stack which is usually enough, but eg. many PPC utils requires
    a much higher stack. See above for an example.

    @{b}PREFIX@{ub}
    Normally Dofile processes the command by simply adding a space between
    the command and the filename: cc:smartplay "x:music/MOD.acid flashback"
    The PREFIX keyword can be used to add some text immediately before the
    filename, like this:
    HTML                          work:voyager/v PREFIX=file:///
    Dofile will now concatate the command and the filename and process it
    like this: work:voyager/v "file:///work:html/32/wdhtml32.htm". This
    keyword was implemented because some Voyager 2.x versions insisted on the
    'file:///' bit when opening a local file.

    When you're finished copy Dofile.prefs to s: 

@endnode
@node usage "Usage"

    rx rexx:Dofile.rexx @{b}FILE,V=VERBOSE/S,D=SHOWDATATYPE/S,S=SHELL/S,
                        I=INSTALL/S,Q=QUIT/S,ARGS/F@{ub}

    @{b}FILE@{ub}
    The file to process. If you pass a directory or nothing as argument to
    Dofile it will open a filerequester. And you can supply a file for
    processing.

    @{b}D=SHOWDATATYPE/S@{ub}
    Displays a requester with the datatype info of the selected file. Also
    shows which command (And the command stacksize) Dofile would use on the
    file. All other options except VERBOSE are ignored.
    
    @{b}V=VERBOSE/S@{ub}
    When processing a file displays a requester with the following info:
    filename, datatype, command name and command stack. 
    When coupled with the SHOWDATATYPE switch it displays a lot more info in
    the requester.

    Note: The stacksize shown in the SHOWDATATYPE/VERBOSE requesters is not
    necessarily the one Dofile will use. If Dofile inherits a larger stacksize
    it will use that instead. Eg: The default stack is 8192 bytes and you have
    configured a command to use 50000 bytes (Using the @{" STACK " link configuration} keyword). But 
    the shell you run Dofile from has a 300000 bytes default stack. So Dofile
    uses 300000 as stacksize but displays 50000 in the requester.

    @{b}S=SHELL/S@{ub}
    Display Dofile output in your shell instead of in requesters. 
    Tip: Add the following alias to your s:shell-startup file:
    "alias do rx rexx:dofile.rexx SHELL"

    @{b}I=INSTALL/S@{ub}
    Installs Dofile (Reads cfgfile and opens Arexx port) without processing
    any files. 
    If you want Dofile installed each time you boot copy the included
    "Dostart.info" icon to your WBStartup drawer. It is not a good idea to
    put it in your user-startup.

    @{b}Q=QUIT/S@{ub}
    Quit Dofile (Close Arexx port).

    @{b}ARGS/F@{ub}
    Any extra arguments that you want to pass to the command. Let's say you
    have configured mpeg viewing like this: "cc:frogger DISPLAY=VLAYERPM2". If
    you want to try watching a movie on a separate screen you can simply do
    this: "rx dofile stor:mpeg/WEIRDISE.MPG SCREEN".
        

    Example: rx Dofile.rexx pix:1.jpg VERBOSE
    
    If you want to change the @{" configuration " link configuration} just edit the Dofile.prefs 
    file. Dofile will detect that it has changed and reload it
    automatically. 

    It's possible to use Dofile as default tool in Workbench project icons.
    I have also replaced SID2's internal filerecognition system with
    Dofile's. Read the @{" notes " link notes} section.
    Additionally I have Dofile installed as a do-it-all Workbench appicon
    (Using ToolManager).

@endnode
@node multiview "Dofile and Multiview"

    If Dofile/datatypes.library can't figure out which datatype a file is it
    returns the file 'master class' which is either "ascii", "binary", "iff"
    or "directory"

    This is why Dofile only checks "ascii", "binary" or "iff" files for file
    @{" patterns " link configuration}. If it is anything else it is either a directory (Which is
    ignored) or a known datatype (Which Multiview hopefully can handle).

    Dofile uses 'Multiview' as default command for known datatypes that you
    haven't configured a command for (Including "ascii" files). If you want to
    change this (To an alternative to Multiview or Multiview with extra
    arguments) you should make sure that this command doesn't try to load
    plain "binary", "iff" or "directory" files.

    Look at the last line the @{" example config file " link dofile.prefs/main} for how to do this.

@endnode 
@node dtdesc "Dofile datatype descriptors"

    Just a few notes about the datatype descriptors in the "desc" directory.
    Most of them are self-explanatory. Here are a few that are not:

    Sources:
    Some of the descriptors (MED among others) are created by me using MakeDT
    v1.3 by Michael Letowski.
    Most descriptors are from various datatype files from aminet (JPEG,
    ProTracker, XBM etc)
    I also got a few descriptors from the archive included with Roland
    Mainz Adddatatypes v45.2.

    I had a problem with the descriptor from Olaf Barthel's MacSND
    datatype. It insisted on scanning any MP3 songs I tried to play making
    it a rather slow affair loading them. Removing the descriptor solved
    the problem.
    
    There's no icons supplied because you can just get what you need from
    your devs:datatypes directory.

@endnode
@node notes "Notes"
    
    @{" How to use Dofile as default tool in Workbench project icons   " link notes_1}
    @{" How to add Dofile to SID2's internal filerecognition system    " link notes_2}
    @{" How to show output of commands started by Dofile               " link notes_3}
    @{" How to use Dofile as your default auto command in DiskMasterII " link notes_4}

@endnode
@node notes_1 "How to use Dofile as default tool in Workbench project icons"

    If you have Workbench 3.5:

        Make sure Dofile has the script bit set. Like so:
        "protect rexx:dofile.rexx +s"

        Now enter "rexx:dofile" as default tool and set the 'Start From' cycle
        gadget to 'Shell'.

        Note that all the ToolAlias patches (Including the one in MCP) doesn't
        work with the new iconformat in WB 3.5.
    
    If you don't have Workbench 3.5:

        First you must make sure that the utility Dofile is in your rexx:
        directory (It's really an utility called @{" RxWB " link rxwb}) together with the 
        Dofile.rexx Arexx script.

        Now you can simply enter "rexx:dofile" as default tool and Dofile will
        automagically start Dofile.rexx with the project as argument.

        If you use one the ToolAlias utilities you can redirect all relevant
        calls to Dofile. Using the Toolalias function in MCP with a pattern
        like this: "(*view*|*guide*|*more*) -> rexx:dofile" works very nicely.

        It's you are using DefIcons (From the NewIcons package) you can simply
        enter "rexx:dofile" as default tool in all the def_#? icons in
        envarc:sys that you wish. 
        I think a ToolAlias patch is the easiest solution :-)

@endnode
@node notes_2 "How to add Dofile to SID2's internal filerecognition system"

    Note: This only works with SID2 v2.01 and newer.

    Add a button called "DOFILE" with the command "run >nil: rx
    rexx:dofile.rexx". Set "Quotes = Yes"

    Make a backup of s:SID2.desc. Select any file you wish and create a new
    description with the ANALYZE button . Name it eg: "Everything" and
    deselect all 12 'identifier' buttons.

    Edit prefs->descriptions. Delete all the entries that you want Dofile
    to handle. Find the "Everything" description at the bottom of the list
    and link it to the DOFILE button.

@endnode
@node notes_3 "How to show output of commands started by Dofile"

    The easiest way is simply running Dofile from your shell. Any output from
    the command is automatically displayed there. You can also switch Dofile's
    requesters completely off with the @{" SHELL " link usage} switch.
    
    Another way is to redirect the output in the config file like this:
    IFF   "cc:visage >CON:////Dofile/AUTO/CLOSE/WAIT"
    But then you cannot view the output in your shell. In the future Dofile
    will probably deal with this in a smarter way.

@endnode
@node notes_4 "How to use Dofile as your default auto command in DiskMasterII"

    Simply edit your startup.dm script so your default auto command looks like
    this:

    AddAutoCmd DEFAULT,Extern run >nil: rx rexx:dofile.rexx "%s"

@endnode
